===Etymology===
[[File:Nicaea icon.jpg|thumb|An [[Orthodox]] [[icon]] depicting the {{w|Constantine the Great}} and the [[bishop]]s of the {{w|First Council of Nicaea}} (325 {{C.E.|dots=yes}}) holding the Niceno–Constantinopolitan Creed of 381, an updated version of the [[Nicene Creed]] prepared by the First Council]]
{{PIE root|en|ḱerd|dʰeh₁}}

From {{inh|en|ang|creda}}, {{m|ang|crede}}, {{m|ang|credo}}, from {{der|en|la|crēdō||I believe}}, from {{der|en|itc-pro|*krezdō}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*ḱred dʰeh₁-||to place one's heart, i.e., to trust, believe}}, a {{glossary|compound}} phrase of the {{glossary|oblique case}} form of {{m|ine-pro|*ḱḗr||heart}}. ''Creed'' is {{glossary|cognate}} with {{cog|sga|cretim||to believe}}, and {{cog|sa|श्रद्दधाति||to have faith or faithfulness, to have belief or confidence, believe}}.

